<subSubSection id="D02D9558ECF6A5D621857ADC9C01AF43" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="type">
<paragraph id="FB22CCF108CA3A98E36BA40B1DF56122" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
<pageBreakToken id="A7942B1B85F7601212C0B63E6519854D" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" start="start">Type</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="553E818B8AFB5B4CF999434A72695495" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
AUSTRALIA, South Australia, 
<emphasis id="99E6F1A8E1A205222937B33F372949BB" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Orchard</emphasis>
2626 (holotype AD!; isotypes NCU, COLO).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E01BE3052DEC7C087F4486CF11C43B09" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="description">
<paragraph id="3DC3325D486B3476F04163B0AE4560D4" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A13736DC670D03B54EEA5B7163A18852" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
Perennial herb from a central taproot with trailing stems to 1 m, plant adpressed pubescent to glabrescent. Leaves petiolate, 1-2 
<normalizedToken id="A9322E9F648C9952D365346AFCD424B8" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.4-05 cm, lanceolate-deltoid, acute, margin entire to slightly undulate, base shallowly cordate and auriculate, the auricles entire or bifid; petioles 3-8 mm long. Flowers solitary, pedunculate, axillary, becoming recurved in fruit; peduncles mostly 1-2 cm long; bracteoles filiform, 1-1.5 mm; pedicels 3-12 mm; outer sepals 2-3(-4) 
<normalizedToken id="477EF2D4D9A81464F38D6439C6E7DF12" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3 mm, obovate to broadly elliptic, rounded and minutely apiculate, scarious, glabrous or thinly appressed pubescent; inner sepals similar; corolla 5-7 mm long, white or pink, very shallowly lobed, midpetaline bands almost glabrous except for a few hairs at apex; ovary glabrous; style glabrous, divided c. 2 mm above base, stigmas c. 1.5-2 mm. Capsule glabrous; seeds coarsely and irregularly tuberculate. [
<bibRefCitation id="F7D26AC65D93A24CB0A1C06369206781" author="Johnson, RW" journalOrPublisher="Austrobaileya" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" pagination="408 - 411" refId="B166" refString="Johnson, RW, 1987. Two new species of Convolvulus L. (Convolvulaceae) from South Australia. Austrobaileya 2: 408 - 411" title="Two new species of Convolvulus L. (Convolvulaceae) from South Australia." volume="2" year="1987">Johnson 1987</bibRefCitation>
: 410-411, figure 1; 
<bibRefCitation id="9D355BBE6543EC473F3FE77F899D241C" author="Johnson, RW" journalOrPublisher="Austrobaileya" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" pagination="1 - 39" refId="B167" refString="Johnson, RW, 2001. A taxonomic revision of Convolvulus L. (Convolvulaceae) in Australia. Austrobaileya 6: 1 - 39" title="A taxonomic revision of Convolvulus L. (Convolvulaceae) in Australia." volume="6" year="2001">Johnson 2001</bibRefCitation>
: 10, figs 3-4, map 1].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="569F06358980D70240CC69774C6AA4DB" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="5A1FE6DA0D6CAD58DDFBD05EE60A3166" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6581DC01DCAFA437B87B228AA5183AD1" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
Australia: South Australia and adjacent New South Wales (
<emphasis id="B52E685A60094317B267669DFA07E387" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Orchard</emphasis>
211, 
<emphasis id="BF7E077FDC516CC860780FE8AA9202DB" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Badman</emphasis>
32, 
<emphasis id="F5100C18D9050E8D80B03D7D3C03EDD3" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Copley</emphasis>
192; 
<emphasis id="6B3CEEB1E9889C9777B2D9B121BE43C3" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Vonow</emphasis>
584, 
<emphasis id="41B70B809AAD8C2F46FBF2EAC7975AD0" italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Mueller</emphasis>
1852).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C8EB8CA53447ED34A69B19E721F6AD84" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="notes">
<paragraph id="EAABA5B174BA1DCBED442CED07CED7F7" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1B3D54866ADB544B39BBBA7E3CDE483C" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Very distinctive because of the tiny calyx, lanceolate-deltoid leaves with basal auricles and the distinctive seed ornamentation.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
